<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36204o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36204o">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36204o"> 204(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Stopped, undressed, advanced</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Dukhobors.]</font> In the spring of 1903, another pilgrimage began, with the additional feature of the men and women taking off their drawers as they approached any sign of life or village. As one of the pilgrims said, &ldquo;We <mark>stopped, undressed, and advanced</mark>.&rdquo; This exhibition had a short life. It was discountenanced by Peter Verigin <font color="green">[one of their sect leaders]</font> and <font color="green">[besides was]</font> stopped at once by the police. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 124</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
